deck_excerpt: Myutant Control with the Dogmatika Engine
deck_description: Myutants burn your own resources too much and too often, but with a control strategy involving floodgates, d shifter, and dogmatika cards, you can also force your opponent to also burn their resources to contend with yours. Strategy: The goal of the deck is very straightforward, and it involves setting up a board of Myutant Beast and/or Myutant Arsenal with at least 1 floodgate and 1 Myutant Cry set. Starters include the 3x Myutant M-05, 3x Myutant ST-46, and 1x E-tele. You then use either Myutant monster starter to search out a spell/trap (usually Myutant Cry) or a monster to go into Myutant Beast or Arsenal, with Beast being the greater priority target. Pot of Prosperity helps quite a lot with searching out the starters/floodgate traps, and Nadir Servant can be used to send extra deck monsters to destroy cards or gain much more resources to restore card advantage. Severable notable combos below: 1. Starting with Myutant Evolution Lab and a Myutant M-05, you can summon M-05, get out ST-46, pitch both to summon Myutant Beast, summon ST-46 from banished with Evolution Lab, and then search out Myutant Cry, with the option to go into Myutant Arsenal or to continue with other plays. 2. Another combo is with Nadir Servant and Myutant ST-46/Myutant Cry in hand. You can use Nadir Servant, send a Myutant Ultimus, search out Dogmatika Maximus, use Maximus to banish the Myutant Ultimus and send Myutant Synthesis + another fusion (usually Titaniklad). By searching out Myutant Cry and/or having it in hand already, you have essentially set up the materials in grave/banished for the fusion summon of Myutant Synthesis for the next turn. Notable Exclusions: Myutant Expansion - While very good for the Myutant archetype overall, cards like summon limit and TCBOO are much more preferred over having this card, which is much slower and does not impact your opponent's gameplan as much as the floodgate traps. Psy-framegear Gamma + Driver - In theory, the psy-framegear package is ideal because it helps prevent your myutant beast/arsenal summon from being ashed. In practice, however, this card is usually a brick even when you are going first. Effect veiler/impermenance screw you much harder anyways, and this deck has ways to continue plays past a negate on your Myutant starters with cards like Nadir Servant and Myutant Evolution Lab. Myutant GB-88 & Myutant Mist - Both of these cards are bad even within their own archetype. Myutant GB-88 is too conditional and is a really bad normal summon, while Myutant Mist is unable to disrupt your opponent's plays (unlike Beast & Arsenal) and therefore is not impactful enough on the board. Notable Inclusions: Shiranui Swordsaga - Because Dimension Shifter forces you to banish cards instead of sending them, it may seems that the Dogmatika engine does not synergize well enough with the hand trap. However, with Shiranui Swordsaga, you can banish it from your extra deck to summon a token, which can be used as fodder to activate both Myutant Beast and Arsenal's quick effects. Dimension Shifter - The best hand trap for this deck. Banishing cards is not a big deal since Myutant Cry and Evolution Lab can make use of banished monsters and the Myutant lvl 8's can recycle banished Myutant spell/traps to the hand. Unlike Ash blossom, which your opponent may be able to play through, an activated Dimension shifter can ruin your opponent's entire turn due to most current decks relying heavily on the graveyard (Tri-brigade, Drytron, Prank-kids, etc.).

Deck Melodius

A high-roll deck which seeks to abuse cards like "necroface" and "left arm offering" to both enable the metaphys engine and disable opponents' decks. While the metaphys cards are designed for a going second playstyle, managing to banish all 3 necrofaces via left arm and/or gold sarcophagus while going first can disrupt any combo or search heavy decks while also generating massive advantage. This decklist can also be tooled to be very budget friendly by replacing high-cost cards with low-cost alternatives (extra deck and side deck specifically). Primary weaknesses of the deck are decks that utilize face-up spell/traps (continuous or pendulum), monster effect immune decks, and imperial order.

deck_excerpt: True Draco Eldlich deck ($125~$200). No extra deck.
deck_description: A combination of True Draco and Eldlich with only the necessary cards.  Pot of Desires and Card of Demise are powerful draw cards, but they have potential downsides so try to use them after seeing your engine pieces. Dragonic Diagram is a great card that can help set up your GY for Eldlich and search your True Draco cards. Monarchs Erupt and Skill Drain can help control the board after you've set up.  Budget options: Cursed Eldland($20 per) → Terraforming+Mystic Mine($9): Provides consistency and forces negate. Evenly Matched($13 per) → Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju($2 per): Helps go 2nd and break boards.  Other cards to consider: Artifact Lancea: Cosmic Cyclone and Evenly Matched hurt the deck a lot. Twin Twisters: faster s/t removal for backrow decks. Domain of the True Monarchs: to lock your opponent out of the extra deck. Called by the Grave / Amano-Iwato / Solemn Strike are all cards to consider.

deck_excerpt: An Vampire deck that utilises the new vampire cards.
deck_description: Welp, as vampires has gotten decent cards in their lineup, I wanted to try using them.  So some key cards:  Vampire ghost ogre: serves as an better version of uni-zombie in vampires(dumps vampire from hand to search an level 4 or higher vampire, and then be able to dump retainer/familiar from deck/banish to provide additional normal summon)  Retainer/familiar: easily searchable/summonable s/t and monster searchers  Uni-Zombie: no explanation needed  Vampire scarlet scourge: when summoned, can bring back any vampire from grave for 1000 lp/summon any monster destroyed by it via battle  Vampire Fraueline: zomibie honest(not opt.)  Vampire Voivode: the main deck boss(genesis sucks too much lol), when brought out on turn 2+ via normal summon, can summon 2 monsters from opponents grave(which can be used for links, sheridan and undead vampire), can special summon itself from gy when a monster is summoned from opponents gy(too easy for vampires tbh), and partial monster effect negation.  (Grace, Duke, and Red Baron are good as one offs imo)  S/T lineup:  Vampire's Desire: Foolish Burial/level changer, as well as an monster reborn in 1 card. 3 c0pies at all times  Vampire's domain: additional normal summons/lifepoint recovery when dealing battle damage(imo 1 is fine due to searchability, but 2 copies can be good too)  Vampire Domination: Archetypal omni negate+lifepoint recovery(3 copies are good, but feel free to run 1-2, as its easily searchable)  Vampire takeover: archetypal metavers/call of the haunted(when field zone is empty): good 1st turn option, bit gets weaker in other turns(run 1-2 copies)  Vampire Empire: Zombies gain 500 atk during damage calculation+ when a card is milled from opponents deck, dump 1 vampire from hand/deck to grave, then destroy 1 card on field(non-tageting). (Decent, but as its easily searchable feel free to run 1-2)  Tech cards:  Foolish Burial: Zombies LOVE the graveyard, so...always use this  Monster reborn: No need for explanation.  Book of life: good 2nd turn card(remove from play 1 monster in opponents grave to summon 1 zombie from your gy)  Called by the grave: no need for explanations here.  Additional tech cards:  Jack-O-Bolan: Can special summon itself from hand by dumping 1 zombie from hand, can banish itself to ss a zobie in either gy(use th ezombie world varian if you want to use this properly  Zombie World: No need for explanation.  Necroworld Banshee: Can search afforementioned field spell(whther on the field or when its in the gy)  Mezuki: again, no need for explanation(banish itself to ss a zombie in your gy)  Gozuki: no need for explation here as well(foolidh burial, and when sent to gy: banish 1 other zomie in the gy to ss a zombie fron hand)  glow-up bloom: when sent to the grave, can banish itself to add an level 5 or higher zombie to your hand, or if "zombie world" is on the field: special summon it(good searcher, but even better with zombie world)  Doomking balderoch: seriously, no need for explantion(good target for glow up blooms special summon effect, can ss itself from the grave when ANY field spell is up during either players standby phase, can once per chain negate an zombie monsters effect, or banish an zombie from either the field or in the opponents gy)(use with zombie world).  Zombie Necronize/Power Struggle is good also.

deck_excerpt: A fun Crusadia/Kaiju deck based on Final Fantasy 7 ^^
deck_description: It is a crusadia otk deck, basically in resume the strategy is seeing your opponent die in the chair while you kaiju a very hard to summon monster or a very expensive omni-negate like dragon. You always wanna go in seccond with this deck. After trying to get the link summoning methods in my head I asked some people in reddit and they told about the crusadia archetype. They even made a deck with this tool in order to me to get the basics of link summoning and I felt in love with it. After watching some videos about the lore of the cards I believed they were inspired in Final Fantasy lore, specifically 7. God even some characters have are very close to the game ( yes I'm talking about those lions and little mages) and a tryceratops tank (in this case the Tryceratops is Thicc). Oh and the Kaijus are basically the weapons. Now the strategies Otk deck = You want to go second Basically you want to see kaijus and crusadia power/arboria in your hand with anything else from the deck other than the trap and the codebreaker. The kaiju allows you to have a clear way from annoying cards (dragon, any despia, plasma or any other hero that is a pain in the ass) to deliver a one punch since maximus doubles equimax/avramax damage, being easily over 8000 and easily oneshoting in turn two. We have four here cuz this is my deck and I made it budget friendly but you could go for 6 even. They are always good to get your hands on and can save you games. Crusadia power basically makes a magius unegatable and unaffected (not by counter traps if you try to chain it) but also makes your monsters nibiru proof. Yea who would thoght about that. And the token? don't worry about it, that is the whole reason of the Link Spider. If your opponent already knows the deal and doesn't summon anything (only way to screw over your otk) or makes you play first you can always go for the Codebreaker (You need to have at least 3 monsters that can special summon themselves from your hand and at least 2 different crusadias) to get a two negate apollousa and a one negate equimax that can get you one of the two world legacy cards in the deck (Krawler basically) to make your opponent regret making you go first. Only weakness about this is our Rocky ''Friend''.   Fire desires if you already have codebreaker or doesn't even need him, or bait the opponent if they have a lot of negates on the field in other to kaiju the other. Twin twister with Arboria, since she is a very good protection, or anything else, any flood gate or anything else will kill your will to play the game, so it is better to be safe than sorry. Always good to have our super dino friend that tributes himself in order to pop one of your opponents card. Jigabytes and Ranryus combos with magius but you could trade them for Parallel Exceed and a Mudskipper. Crusadia basics : Magius= Searcher Draco= Extender Arboria= Protection Power= Bless Avramax= To take the trash out Spatha= Good to make your opponent regret their normal summon Regulex= Spell searcher Equimax= Literally one punch horse Oh and if you are against a control or stun deck, pray, alot actually. And remember, it is my deck with my budget. You can always improve and upgrade it to new other levels. Hope you enjoyed ^^

deck_excerpt: The year is 2031, Konami has released in the last competitive set a unavoidable hand trap that locks you from normal summon, this deck become tier 0.
deck_description:
Win without normal summon.

  This is an OTK deck where you have only one combo. I chose infernoids becouse they are the only (not sure) monsters easy to special summon and that cannot be special summoned by other ways so perfect target to monster Gate/Reasoning. To make the main combo you will need the right cards in hand and good RNG to extract it's maximum potential.   The right cards in hand are Guardian Dreadscythe (the boss monster), 2 low level infernoid monsters and a monster gate. There's a secondary version with just Guardian Dreadscythe and Reasoning.   Good RNG, it's basically don't end the game sending the 2 Dreadscythe's equip spell to the graveyard while gotting the maximum of monsters in the grave. Monster gate and reasoning interactions with this deck are really interesting because instead of using them to summon a random monster we use to send tons of monsters to the graveyard and summon only one. Also... I need some sleep, ill finish this guide later zzzz.   !1!update; I'm back :) If you already have the right cards in hand; this is the combo with monster gate (With Reasoning just trigger and jump to the third step):
  1. Summon a low level infernoid or a Photon Thrasher.
  2. Use monster gate on the it and see the magic happening.
  3. Good RNG, if you are luck you may get a tons of monster in the grave.
  4. Monster gate/Reasoning special summon Eatos.
  5. If Infernoid Onuncu was send to the grave or is in your hand, special summon and active it effect, destroying Eatos and any enemy monsters with no protection on the field.
  6. After Eatos has been destroyed you can active Guardian Dreadscythe in your hand, special summoning him and in sequence equipping Reaper Scythe - Dreadscythe.
  7. At this point you have a spell/trap negate and a BEG beatstick so just destroy your enemy.

Notes:

  The whole deck is made for this combo and will break if you got 2 Eatos in hand or send 2 Reaper Scythe to the graveyard. Is easily disrupted by any trap deck or decks using ash blossom so i recommend you to use against friends and other casual decks. At least until 2031. Pot of prosperity is bad since you may not win in one turn but helps alot to get a perfect hand. Hidden Armory can save you from losing by having no Reaper Scythe in deck and can search Power of Guardians to protect your boss monster. Infinite Impermanence is the only hand trap i could think that can't be special summoned, psy-framegear gama could've been a very good hand trap for this deck but unfortunately you would need at least one psy-frame driver and that would add one more layer of RNG to the combo. !2!Update: Added Photon Thrasher.   Sorry fo any grammar mistakes. Any suggestions are welcome.

deck_excerpt: How fast can you summon a level 10 or 11 synchro signer dragon?
deck_description: Lot of brain power to drive this deck, many many ways to end on your boss monsters.  Use Junk Converter to search the Synchron you need; if you have Junk Synchron I usually go for Synchron Carrier first for the additional normal summon of Junk Synchron which then brings back Junk Converter.  Go into a 5 with Converter and Synchron.  Junk Speeder is a good option for specialing more tuners to field.  Junk Speeder chain 1, Converter chain 2 to bring back Junk Synchron or a different tuner if you used Converter, and Carrier chain 3 for a level 2 token.  From there you can go into whatever you need. Most optimal route is opening either of the new Stardust monsters and Stardust Illumination.  Activate Illumination to Foolish Burial the other Stardust; Stardust Trail if you drew Stardust Synchron and vice versa, normal summon a monster and activate the Stardust Synchron tributing the monster to special summon Synchron.  Search off the Synchron summon for Arrive in Light and activate Trail to special summon.  Activate Arrive in Light to stack Converging Wills Dragon then synchro summon Stardust.  Chain 1 Arrive in Light chain 2 Stardust Trail.  Stardust Trail will summon a level 1 token then draw the Converging Wills with Arrive, activate the Wills and summon it off the draw.  Activate Illumination in grave to increase Stardust Dragon to level 9 then synchro for 11 and you have your Shooting Majestic Star Dragon. There's so many ways to toolbox your way around you're just going to have to test the deck to find.  Way too many to type out here.  Give it a shot, pretty fun deck and can get exceptionally mean if it goes full combo.  Oh yea, can also play through a negate sometimes depending on your draw but not always, good thing to point out.

After making Ciphers irl and playing post DAMA Zombies online, I'm back. The only interaction Eldlich has with Vampires is that your Eldlixirs can summon Vampires and Vampire's Domain is a continuous spell that Golden Lord can make use of. You go first with this Deck. 3 Ash, 2 Golden Lord, 1 Vampire Baron which helps with stealing monsters, 3 Scarlet Scourge which also helps with stealing and reviving Vampires, 3 Retainer which searches spells/traps, and 3 Familiar which searches monsters. 3 Vampire Ghost Ogre. It ROTAs for a Vampire and either sends Retainer or Familiar to grave and it is also a quick eff Normal Summon. You want to use Familiar to search Ghost Ogre for a follow-up next turn and you would want to search either Vampire's Domain or Vampire Domination with Retainer for more plays this turn or disruption. Spells/Traps: 2 Eldlixir of Black Awakening which summons a Zombie from deck which is most important. 1 Eldlixir of White Destiny. 3 Eldland. 3 Vampire's Domain which is still a great additional normal summon enabler and a way to get back those LP you just burn through. 1 Vampire's Desire. Vampire Ghost Ogre is your main source of a Foolish and Scourge is a lest costly revive so you don't quite need it. 3 Prosp. 3 Scarlet Sanguine which summons a Zombie from Deck or Grave most importantly. 3 Conq. 2 Huaq. 1 Vampire's Domination which is a searchable omni-negate. You could bump Huaq to 3 if you cut Vampire's Desire also. Extra: 1 Zeus. 1 Gaia Charger. 1 Dragulas for style points tbh. 2 The Undead Vampire which is just untargetable Chaos Ruler that can yoink a monster that you milled from either player's Deck. This isn't Control Zombies so you are going to have to make it using 2 stolen monsters which isn't that hard with Scourge, Baron, Sheridan, and Crackdown. 2 Vampire Sheridan which can send a card to Grave and it can also steal a monster that was sent to the Grave by card effect. 1 Vampire Knight Bram which also steals monsters and you can make it using Golden Land Traps. It recurs itself so its okay at 1. 1 Accesscode. 1 BLS Link. 1 Vampire Fascinator which is honestly here to link off monsters. It isn't that great here as compared to in Control Zombies. 3 Vampire Sucker. 1 Knightmare Phoenix. Side Deck: 1 Vampire Voivode which is definitely playable but isnt that great except for very niche situations. 3 Nib. 3 Kaijus. 1 Vampire Fraulein which is good but since we are playing actual Vampire cards, it isn't as versatile due to you constantly burning LP. 3 Twin Twister. 1 more Vampire Domination and 3 Crackdown.

deck_excerpt: Blue-eyes with Invoked engine. Control the flow of the game !!!
deck_description: This is an better and updated list to the v1 list that I released earlier this month I have had some time to really understand the deck's strengths and weaknesses, I have make some significant changes to the deck to make to run more consistently and address the previous issue of going first and not being able to counter your opponent effectively.  Cards cut Ash Blossom, Invoked Purgatrio, Dragon Shrine, Dragon Revival Rhapsody, and Twin Twisters (moved to side deck)  Card ratio's change Blue-Eyes, Aleister, Effect Veiler, White Stone of Ancients, Invocation, and Silver's Cry.  So my thought process to get this build was one of two things, cut cards/change ratio's stopping the deck from being consistent and having less brink hands. For example I changed the ratio's for the Invoked engine so that one it don't brink but you also still get good value out of it, support cards like newly added "Terraforming" and "Foolish Burial" allow allow for the deck to have easy access to Aleister and Meltdown. Now you might be thinking why would you wanna foolish an Aleister well if you open or draw into Invocation you can foolish Aleister to grave and then Invocation is fully live as you would banish Aleister from grave and it becomes a plus 3 as Aleister would be added to hand you'd have a Invoked Fusion monster on board and Invocation back to deck via effect. In terms of the Blue-eyes engine I changed the ratio's for both Ancients and Blue-eyes with Ancients the grave effect is the most important so that if you need to discard a Blue-eyes or Alternative you can add them back, with Blue-eyes I changed the ratio to 3 previously I said not to play Blue-eyes at 3 unless you decided to play "Mausoleum of White".  The thought process here was 1 Blue-eyes is a hand lock one is a grave lock and the third is open to be used in the way you need it to be, you need one in hand mainly for Alternative plays can be used for Trade-In plays and added back with Ancients or Seyfert. With the extra deck I substituted "Invoked Purgatrio" for "Number 68: Sanaphond The Sky Prison" for 2 reasons one because Purgatrio is harder to use as Ash was cut from this build so it would rely on opponents using Ash or them playing Fire type monsters which is not realistic or consistent and two Sky Prison is more consistent as it's a rank 8 that makes opponents have to overextend if there deck is grave special summon reliant.  Master and Sage are your MVP tuners, Master can also be used to get a rank 8 play off with "Linkuriboh" which is a mini combo in this build which would summon Master get normal summon effect if not negated you can add ideally a Sage of Veiler back to hand then link it off for Linkuriboh use Master effect in grave target Linkuriboh and special summon a Blue-Eyes monster. In terms for going for Synchro plays it all based on the duel situation if you to play more aggressive use Crocodragon and if you need to play more defensive play Spirit Dragon package, Cloudcastle can be used from defensive or aggressive but ideally only use it if you have another level 9 monster in grave so you can go into Enterblathnir which yes it gets over Dragoon.  If you have any questions or recommendations please feel free to leave a comment and I'll get back to as soon as I can.

deck_excerpt: A highly oppressive going-second Dinosaur deck featuring a Shaddoll engine. This deck is very consistent, can play through multiple negates/disruption
deck_description: Gain access to your boss monster, the ultimate apex predator: Ultimate Conductor Tyranno, using Souleating Oviraptor, or summon it through Double Evolution Pill, searchable with Overtex Qoatlus and Animadorned Archosaur, in order to crush your opponent with it's immense sheer force! This deck can also utilize Shaddoll Fusion to lay down extremely suppressive fusion monsters such as El Shaddoll Winda, Construct, and Apkallone, while also triggering the various GY effects of the Shaddoll monsters used as materials, as well as a few of the Dinosaur monsters, such as the aforementioned Overtex Qoatlus, or to send Miscellaneousaurus to the GY in a pinch to summon Animadorned Archosaur! Two basic combos: Combo 1: Shaddoll Fusion -- While your opponent controls a monster that was special summoned from the extra deck, you can activate Shaddoll Fusion to send one of your four Shaddoll monsters to the GY, as well as Overtex Qoatlus, in order fusion summon El Shaddoll Winda, and to gain the effect of the Shaddoll monster used as material, as well as add a Double Evolution Pill from your deck to your hand. From there, since you can only special summon one more time this turn due to El Shaddoll Winda's effect, activate Double Evolution Pill to banish the materials used to summon El Shaddoll Winda to summon Ultimate Conductor Tyranno from your deck! Combo 2: Souleating Oviraptor and Babycerasaurus -- Normal summon Souleating Oviraptor and use it's effect to add Miscellaneousaurus from your deck to your hand. From here, activate Miscellaneousaurus' effect in your hand to discard it. Now, not only are your Dinosaur monsters well protected from your opponent's card effects, you can banish Miscellaneousaurus to summon Animadorned Archosaur from your deck. Next, activate Animadorned Archosaur's effect to destroy the Babycerasaurus in your hand and add a Double Evolution Pill from your deck to your hand, and Since Babycerasaurus was destroyed by a card effect, you can activate it's effect, and summon a second copy of Babycerasaurus. Here's where things get tricky. Activate Souleating Oviraptor's effect to destroy the new Babycersaurus, and special summon one of the two copies of Babycerasaurus back from your GY. Since Babycerasaurus is not Once Per Turn, you can use it's effect again because it was destroyed by Souleating Oviraptor. Special summon Giant Rex from your deck. Next, link summon Linkuriboh using Animadorned Archosaur, then link summon Secure Gardna using Linkuriboh. After that, activate Double Evolution Pill to banish Linkuriboh and the remaining Babycerasaurus in your GY to summon Ultimate Conductor Tyranno from your deck. Finally, xyz summon one of your two Evolzar monsters using Souleating Oviraptor and Giant Rex. During your opponent's turn, Ultimate Conductor Tyranno can destroy Babycerasaurus and flip all of your opponent's monsters face down, and then since Babycerasaurus was destroyed by a card effect, you can special summon a new level 4 or lower Dinosaur monster! Try summoning another Souleating Oviraptor to add another Dinosaur monster  to your hand who will help you out next turn!

deck_description: hi hi everyone welcome to the new brand Magistus deck, well I decide to edit the deck once again ( my lase Magistus deck was < Magistus supercharge > ) so in this deck we removed some useless negate cards and we're using < ecclesia, the virtuous in white > cuz it's free special summon and she's a tuner which means more access to our synchros and it can be special summoned by Zoroa's effect. and i add < ready fusion > to bring <kamionwizard > his spellcaster normal fusion monster and <number 41: Bagooska > which helps us better than Zeus. OKAY since I explained fewer combos last time I'll explain all things now  To start you only need one of the Magistus monsters and one of their spells and it's better be not < Aleister the Crowley > cuz it's hard, to start with it. the first thing you need to do is to XYZ summon < Rilliona, the wonderous Magistus witch wardrobe > ( warning do not XYZ summon Ninaruru we never gonna summon that card  understand !! ) after you do special summon  < Zoroa, the Magistus of flame > equipped with Ninaruru or whatever you wanted just be careful what type of monsters your opponent playing in the extra deck. and then we're going to synchro summon < Zoroa, the Magistus of daimon > then if had field spell < secret village of spellcasters > activate that, don't limit the field spell we need that much more then other cards but if your opponent were playing a spellcaster archetype just find a way to summon < Aiwass, the Magistus spell spirit > and take control of it when he summoned that.  you may ask what < PSY-Framelord Omega > doing here, well if you think he's only here to return your banished Magistus monsters you're wrong the first reason I added that card was to return back < Magistus Vritra >Magistus Vritra is the only way to protect your equipped Magistus monsters and cards when you don't have your field spell, you should not summon Omega first turn you need him in your second turn.  well let's look at the extra deck we 3 additional hand traps ( Nibiru - droll & lock bird - artifact Lancea ) you only gonna replace them with ash blossom and ghost belle, also we have 2 other synchro monsters to replace with other synchros < Adamancipator Risen - Dragite > & < stardust Dragon > but you can also use < Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend > and for the last be careful when using < Magistus theurgy > you can even use that on your opponent turn.  anyways yup don't forget this archetype hasn't finished yet, there are 4 or more supports cards left to come in the future due to their story  till next time see ya  (< Magistus EDITION 25 >)

Yo, this is my fist time using Brave Token engine.
  I've made another Magistus deck before this and thought in just updating instead of sending another, but this new version with Brave Token engine is much different. What this deck do is basically synchro summon in the start and in the late game otk with a big link combo. The only reliable turner in the deck is Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame and even with only one turner the deck is consistent. Magistus archtype is very flexible so you don't have only one combo to do and is always situational. Spellbook engine is easy and give you a draw 2. Brave Token engine uses many cards but is easy too, Just ~activate Rite of Aramesia ~then Journey of Destiny ~With journey take Wandering Gryphon Rider but if you are planning in Synchro summon with the token DON'T take Gryphon, take Aquamancer instead and stop here ~if you added a Gryphon then special summon him and activate Journey of Destiny to equip your token with his exclusive equip spell ~active the equip spell effect if you need, Gryphon is a omni negate by the way.   Sorry for any grammar mistakes. Any suggestions are welcome.

I have been building this deck for some months now and been testing on different simulations sites. This deck is pretty good at interruption,swarming and recovery which I'd likely recommend for beginners and intermediate players. Although banish Myutants are much popular than Dogmatikas given that Dogmatikas itself are more expensive cards, it doesn't take away the fun of going toe to toe against with both rogue and meta decks. It's easy  to use that it just follow the same pattern as the Shadoll Invoke where you usually start with Aliester, here you starts with the smaller myutants waiting to get to get interrupted by Ash, Veiler or Impermanence then proceed to Almiraj then Dogmatikas. Swarming is pretty easy and just like Shadoll Invoke, you have to keep in mind to fusion first before using the dogmatika cards. The synergy of this two archetypes is really high given that Myutants are the offensive stance while Dogmatikas set the GY and field for defensive purposes. Extra deck monsters are versatile depends on the situation,.you got toadally for recovery , Titaniklad for the dogmatika setup, Pegasus and Harbinger for defense and lastly, Numeron dragon for offense which you can fully utilize it's effect even if it got destroyed by card effect (Presumably you can set Myutant Cry or any Myutant traps from your GY). Overall, this is the peak iteration of my Myutant build I've been making for months. Hope this helps, good luck and have fun.

deck_excerpt: Predaplant Control build, aimed to play as competitively as possible.
deck_description: Greetings! Today i will show you people my actual Predaplant build, this is a control variant as opposed to my board wipey one from before so wear your seat belts because this is going to be an interesting ride! Summary: 1- Card Explanation 2- Deck's Objective and/or Wincon 3- Combos 4- Math Card Explanation:   Staples-<!--more--> 3x Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring (Hand Trap) 3x Pot of Desires (Draw power and card advantage, as well as baiting negates) 1x Called by the Grave (Negating field stuff and protecting some of your combos) 1x Foolish Burial (Send some stuff to the GY, primarily acts as a pseudo rota for the PK extender) 2x Super Polymerization (Counter every DARK deck and some more!, this card is searchable in this deck and is at least a 2 of) 1x Instant Fusion (Can act as a better Called by the Grave in a sense that the monster brought out is a fusion, can be searched AND be used in a specific 1 card combo) Engines- <!--more--> 3x Edge Imp Chain (It is quite useful in generating card advantage and minimizing your fusion costs) 2x Frightfur Patchwork (Can be searched by the aforementioned Edge Imp Chain and search a Polymerization by having no cost at all!) 1x Polymerization (Classic fusion stuff, nothing else to be said) 1x Fusion Substitute (Just like above but with a spice in card advantage and recycling) 1x The Phantom Knights of Ancient Cloak (Can be used as a cost for a fusion or Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and then, search an extender or The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots that is made for fetching Phantom Knights' Fog Blade) 1x The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots (Used to search Fog Blade) 2x Phantom Knights' Fog Blade (Searchable easy negate, makes any Predaplant Chimerafflesia into a negate) 1x The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine (A searchable extender that is also used in a very specific combo) Now last but not least... The Garden- <!--more--> 3x Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio (One of the 7 normal summons, is crucial in a lot of combos but is very fragile to negates, good thing that we have some stuff that mediates that right?) 3x Predaplant Chlamydosundew (Yep, i just typed that out of my head, it is one of the 7 normal summons and is a GREAT card to stabilish control once Predator Counters are all over the field) 1x Predaplant Spinodionaea (The last normal summon and not that great, however he is useful in his ways and can put a single counter on the field, largely useful in going second situations) 2x Predaplant Sarraceniant (The blocker hand trap, can search too!, much wow, such useful) 1x Predaplant Cordyceps (A garnet, can be sent to the GY for some interesting setups that will be explained later) 1x Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra (The snek, a garnet and can search every fusion stuff this deck has) 1x Predaplant Drosophyllum Hydra (Also wrote that out of my head, a garnet and pseudo-kaiju) 3x Predapractice (Search spell AND extender, honestly the card is quite bad but i managed to make some use out of it, in this specially crafted decklist it is phenomenal) 1x Predaprime Fusion (My "third Super Polymerization" but for free!, is used whenever you have a Predaplanning pop setup of just need a way to quick fuse to escape targeting) 3x Predaplanning (One of your wincons honestly, this card is the whole reason i made this control build, can send a target as cost and splatter Predator Counters all over the field) EXTRA DECK- <!--more--> 2x El Shaddoll Winda (She is used in specific going first combos) 1x Millennium-Eyes Restrict(Is a pseudo Called by the Grave and can be used to safely and easily make a Predaplant Dragostapelia) 1x Mudragon of the Swamp (Super Polymerization target) 3x Predaplant Chimerafflesia (Your main beater honestly, can crack up her own ATK by 1k and can banish some annoying Ecclesias) 2x Predaplant Dragostapelia (Her along Predaplanning are your main control cards, she is currently the wincon of the deck, get her out as soon as possible) 2x Predaplant Triphyoverutum (A Super Polymerization target as well as a secondary boss monster, big beatstick) 1x Starving Venom Fusion Dragon (A Super Polymerization target who can also double as a big and menacing beatstick, plus points if you copy a Mechaba or Construct's effects and identity) 1x Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss (An enabler of the Phantom Knights engine and can protect your monsters, is a part of some combos) 1x Predaplant Verte Anaconda (BIG snek, is a surprise Super Polymerization) 1x The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche (Is another enabler of the Phantom Knights engine and can setup 2 negates, such wow, very useful) Theory- <!--more--> This deck aims to control the board by placing Predator Counters which in turn make monsters affected by them level 1 and basically abusable by the user. Predaplant Chlamydosundew can use monsters with Predator Counters DARK and usable to fusion summon Predaplant Drosophyllum Hydra can kaiju those same monsters away with no response for your opponent Predaplant Spinodionaea can summon a Predaplant from the deck if he battles a monster with lower level than him, all within the damage step Predaplant Dragostapelia is the deck's main wincon, negating the effects of all monsters your opponent controls with a counter and can also put counters herself huh! Predaplant Triphyoverutum is the secondary boss monster who can negate a special summon from the extra, primarily Xyz, Synchro and Link, AND turn into a giant behemoth under certain conditions Predaplanning is the main wincon of this deck along the aforementioned monsters, being able to set up and send a plant from the deck as cost and put counters is highly unassuming, only certain people will acknowledge this card as a real threat so it will mostly pass without any interaction. Combos- <!--more--> Well, here are some simple combos that have a HUGE payoff, let me explain them: Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio + Edge Imp Chain: Normal Ophrys-> Send Chain as cost-> Special Cobra-> Cl1 Cobra,Cl2 Chain-> Add Patchwork + Instant Fusion or any Fusion card-> Make Cherubini using Cobra and Ophrys-> Activate Cherubini by sending Ancient Cloak-> Search Shade Brigandine via Ancient Cloak-> Summon Shade-> Make Bardiche-> Activate Bardiche, send Boots then set Fog Blade-> Activate Instant Fusion-> Summon Winda-> Activate Patchwork-> Add Chain + Fusion Sub-> Activate Fusion Sub-> Make Dragostapelia or the second Winda-> Search the second Fog Blade via Boots-> Activate Fusion Sub by shuffling Winda back to the extra deck thus drawing a card-> set the second Fog Blade. (End Board: 2 Monster Negates/Winda/+3 Card Advantage) Predaplant Chlamydosundew + Edge Imp Chain: Normal Summon Chlamydosundew->Fusion into Chimerafflesia using Chain and Sundew-> Activate Chain's effect thus adding Patchwork-> Search Polymerization and Chain via Patchwork-> Make Dragostapelia using Chimerafflesia and Chain->Seach a Fusion Spell via Chimerafflesia next standby. (End Board: 1 Negate/Predator Counter Placement/+0 Card Advantage but Superpoly Searchable) Cordyceps Combinations: It can be easily sent to the GY via Predaplanning so sending it to the GY is not a problem. The combos with him include but are not limited to: Spinodionaea + Chlamydosundew: Special both-> Put a counter via Spino's effect-> Fuse via Chlamydosundew into Starving Venom/Triphyoverutum or Chimerafflesia. (End board: 1 Big Fusion, Your Opponent is negged 1) Sarraceniant + Chlamydosundew: Special both-> Fuse into Chimeraffleia or Starving Venom-> Search a Predap card. (End board: 1 Big fusion + Any Predap card) Darlingtonia Cobra + Sarraceniant: Special both-> Search any fusion card if you didn't proc Darlingtonia before or she was in your starter hand-> Fuse into Starving Venom or Chimerafflesia->Proc Sarraceniant for any Predap card. (End board: 1 Big fusion + Any Predap card) Math- <!--more--> As a going first deck, i did every calculation based on 5 cards on hand. You have 43% of opening 1 normal summon You have 59% of opening 2 normal summons You have 12% of opening 1 normal summon + Predapractice You have 16% of opening 2 normal summons + Predapractice You have 16% of opening 1 Oprhys Scorpio or Chlamydosundew + 1 Edge Imp Chain You have 24% of opening up to 2 Oprhys Scorpio or Chlamydosundew + up to 2 Edge Imp Chain You have 14% of opening 1 Oprhys Scorpio or Chlamydosundew + 1 PK engine card You have 25% of opening up to 3 Predaplants + up to 3 Predapractice You have 10% of opening any of the normal summons + Instant Fusion or Called by the Grave You have 34% of opening a normal summon + Predaplanning You have 40% of opening a staple + a normal summon   End- Well, this is the end, the deck is still in development and awaiting any support from konami, thus i hope that i will get some anime cards like Lilyzard or Ivy Bind Castle. The problem with the deck is the lack of in archetype extenders and ways to stop your opponent's plays, the amount of resources needed to make Dragostapelia is also a problem, if she was easier to do like Chimerafflesia then i wouldn't be mad at it. Thank you for your time here and hope you have an interesting day.

Que tal amigos, aqui tenemos un deck cortesia de Ale Mucci. Este es un mazo con el que muchas estrategias basadas en efectos de cartas que, ya sea que activen cuando son enviadas cementerio o que activen estando en el mismo, tienen bastantes problemas; o si juegas un deck combo con mas de 4 invocaciones pasaras un mal rato ante la poca capacidad que tendrás de reciclar recursos del cementerio. Esto es gracias a que la principal fortaleza de esta baraja es BANEAR con cartas como Dimension Shifter, Macro Cosmos y Dimensional Fissure no importa si va de turno 1 o 2, si no tenemos como evitar la activación/resolución de los efectos de estas, se nos hara muy complicado el duelo conforme pasan los turnos; lo que beneficia a los Ritual Beast, pues son capaces de jugar alrededor de este ban con cartas como Ritual Beast Tamer Wen, su magia rápida Ritual Beast Return, y algunos de sus monstruos de fusion, que son capaces de regresar al Extra Deck e invocar de forma especial 2 de sus monstruos baneados estos son Ritual Beast Ulti-Pettlephin, Ritual Beast Ulti-Apelio y Ritual Beast Ulti-Cannahawk. Aunado a esto, aprovecha lo anterior para escalar en los link con Harpie Conductor ya que solo necesita 2 mounstruos de viento y asi llegar a Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty con quien en la End Phase invoca otro floodgate en la forma de Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds, con lo que se acaban las invocaciones especiales de todo aquello que no sea atributo viento. Ya para finalizar aunque no menos importante, si todo lo anterior falla siempre esta la vieja confiable de usar kaijus y quitarse de inicio algún monstruo molesto, para asi poder usar los efectos del XYZ Lightning Chidori con quien no solo podremos quitarnos algun Set que tenga el oponente, si no que tambien podemos reciclar nuestro kaiju al desacoplar un material a Chidori y mandar nuestro kaiju al tope de nuestro mazo. Para conocerlo mejor, solo descargarlo y pruebalo en tu app/programa para jugar YGO! en linea. Nos vemos y..., Buen Duelo.

Then give your Opponent one Impcantation-Monster in defense position and deal 8k piercing DMG :D Search for Ritual Monster: - 3x Bingo Machine, Go!!! - 3x The Melody of Awakening Dragon - 3x Impcantation Candoll with a Ritual Spell (Impcantation Candoll special Impcantation Talismandra from the Deck and Impcantation Talismandra search for Ritual Monster -3x Manju of the Ten Thousand Hand Search for Ritual Spell: -3x Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands -3x Impcantation Talismandra with a Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon (Impcantation Talismandra special Impcantation Candoll from the Deck and Impcantation Candoll search for Ritual Spell)   so I play a few test rounds, there is a high Chance to summon Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon and u can play through 1 to 2 Handtraps. deck_excerpt: try to negate everything with Herald of Perfection
deck_description: Deck Strategy: -> summon Herald of Perfection with Impcantation-Combo -> use Cyber Angel Benten as Material to search for Vanity's Ruler -> summon Vanity's Ruler with the two Impcantation-Monsters as tribute Search for Ritual Monster / Spell: - Preparation of Rites can search both Ritual Monsters - Pre-Preparation of Rites search for Herald of Perfection AND Dawn of the Herald - Diviner of the Heralds mills Herald of the Arc Light from the Extra-Deck to the Graveyard. The Herald search then for 1 Ritual Monster OR 1 Ritual Spell - Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands search for 1 Ritual Monster OR 1 Ritual Spell Remember: Chain 1: Cyber Angel Benten -> Chain 2: Dawn of the Herald ==> Opponent cant react to Chain 1, bec. there is already a Chain 2. deck_excerpt: Nordic Brave Token deck with ratio explanation, combo guide, and duels.
deck_description:
https://youtu.be/sb6WAO2WiXA With new Nordic support from Battle of Chaos set and Brave Token. Combo and matchup is in the video down below. There are 2 combo lines being used here. 4-3-3: Ivaldi+Gullinbursti+Tanngnjostr, in this line it's better to make Thor because it provides 2 recursions (Thor eff and new trap eff). 4-4-2: Ivaldi+Alviss+Vanadis send Mara, in this line it's better to make Loki/Odin because we use both Nordic Alfar tuner and Nordic Ascendant tuner (2 recursions: Loki/Odin eff and Alviss GY eff). This combo line is added because Zeus is able to wipe the 4-3-3 line endboard and turns off both the 2 revives (Thor eff and new trap eff), despite the combo giving more advantage.   Main Deck
  • 3 Alviss: One of the best normal summon because we will have guaranteed recursion if it's in the GY. It got great GY eff, so we run 1 each of the Aesir at least to freely choose which one is perfect for the situation. The first effect is kinda niche, as you need to send 1 monster you control, means you will lack material for regular synchro summon as Alviss effect is not treated as proper synchro summon.
  • 3 Ivaldi, 1 RotA: The new Nordic support, best normal summon because it allows the 4-3-3 line to get full advantage (add this card back from GY via Gullinbursti, summon it next turn).
  • 2-3 Gullinbursti: Only 2 because it cannot add itself back if using the 4-3-3 line, especially if you run smaller Nordic lineup, you don't really wanna draw this name on the first turn if you only open 1 Nordic monster.
  • 2 Tanngnjostr/Tanngrisnir: Just another Nordic name, but play 2 since its needed in 4-3-3 line to summon from deck.
  • 1 Vanadis, 1 Mara: For the 4-4-2 combo line. Vanadis is a Nordic Ascendant for Odin revival, while Mara is a Nordic Alfar for Loki. Mara also allows Halqifibrax play (either for Selene Accescode or Shooting Riser sending Aquamancer or Token Collector).
  • 1 Nordic Relic trap each (Gungnir and the new Valinn): Valinn is super good negation with revival (1 eff per turn) while Gungnir doesn't need Aesir name to interrupt.
  • I don't run the new Nordic Relic spell Hildskjalf because the e-tele eff locks us to Aesir (yeah the link 1 is Nordic, can't summon that) and the GY eff negs us because it needs a shuffle back. We'd rather run more Nordic monster than drawing Foolish Burial Goods to achieve the same.
  • Regular Brave Token lineup: 3 Aquamancer, 3 Rites of Aramesia, 1 Foolish Burial, 1 Journey of Destiny, 1 Wandering Gryphon Rider, and 1 Dracoback the Dragonsteed equip.
  • 3 Hippo Carnival: Seems random but you can chain this to summon 3 tokens as link 1 Gullveig banish fodders.
  • The rest is just staples.
  Extra Deck
  • 2-3 Gullveig link 1: Only 2, because it's hard to resolve the third one, and by that time we're already lose/win anyway.
  • The Aesirs: 1 each for Alviss play, but play more Thor and Loki. Thor gives you potential bait/crackback if summoned via Alvis GY eff. Loki recurs any trap by reviving itself, it means the opponent has to think if they want to remove our trap before removing Loki as Loki can add it back, while at the same time Loki is protected by our link 1 Gullveig making it harder to remove before the trap. Loki creates a mindgame, huh nothing new.
  • Halq play: Selene, Accesscode, Shooting Riser
  • The rest is just generic toolbox.
  Side Deck

Format and matchup specific

deck_excerpt: Orcust Danger! deck by YGO Lite
deck_description: https://youtu.be/xHOWzH3fqGQ
Dark Magicians Archetype Deck
Summon a big dumb train and hit hard

Fun in the Stun. Your win conditions: -Ophion hard counters whatever you're facing.  You can kick back and relax, just do whatever you have to do to make him stick. -Ophion doesn't counter whatever you're facing, but TCBOO/Gozen or even Macro/D. Fissure does.  Basically the same scenario above.  Make your floodgate stick, and beat over things.  You probably make Ophion anyway, because it's Evilswarm and that's just what you do. -You stunned them with hand traps, and they leave a board with a 2k or lower ATK monster that you Utopia Double OTK over.  Congrats on not making Ophion. -You make Origin, and your opponent just really wants to try their shiny new Destroy Phoenix Enforcer, and they keep making you +1 because they haven't seen this deck in 8 years.  That or you made Exciton/Raigeki'd under Origin and got a huge plus, those are always nice. Ophion still beats a lot of things by itself, assuming you can protect it from things like Cerb, Unicorn, etc.  Room for 9 hand traps.  I run D. Shifter, Ash, and Imperm with a set of Droll in the side.  Gozen is a must since it generally checks whatever TCBOO doesn't.  You can probably swap Judgements for Strikes, but I like Judgement for floodgate protection.  Torrential is fun to play with considering Origin, making it an incredibly viable tech choice.  I like Prosperity over Allure by far, since you can pitch 6 from your extra pretty safely to give you a lot of flexibility from that search.  You're very vulnerable to Ash considering Prosperity and Rabbit getting hit hurt a ton, but that's just life.  The deck is 8 years old at this point, this was the best I can do, give me a break. Other Notes: -Keep Mandragora in the side, it's not worth the main slots.  You pray that you go 1st and establish Ophion Game 1.  Focus on nothing else. -Thunderbird is trash, don't run it. -Allure is OK if Prosperity is out of budget. -Iron Dragon Tiamaton is still very fun, and can easily lock your opponent out of both Links and Level 5's if you summon Ophion to your EMZ, and lock out theirs with Tiamaton.  Tech it in for casual play, but it's probably not viable for competitive play, especially after you first drop it.

deck_excerpt: The format has progressed and Miragestallio's roamed free for a few months so it's time to update the deck accordingly
deck_description: We're still under the same banlist and have roughly the same format as last time when I uploaded my previous Salamangreat decklist. hOwEvEr, I've made some changes since then. Salamangreat Miragestallio has been out for a while now and I think I've grasped a better feel for when and how to use it compared to last time.  Because of that I've cut some cards and added some others, alongside some regular changes to the deck like updating handtraps, improving on some ratios, etc.   Up until recently I played both Salamangreat Fowl and Sea Archiver at 1 copy each. Both can "chainblock" very important effects like Wolf's monster recursion and most notably, Gazelle's mill. I played Fowl mostly since it got a shiny new print in Ghost from the Past but have now cut it in order to play Archiver at 2. Archiver is fantastic. Not so fantastic that I want to see it constantly, it is "only" an extender after all, which I'm not too dependent on, but being able to send it with Cynet Mining or Flame Bufferlo without losing out on it's effect is fantastic and chainblocking not when you perform a Link Summon (which is when a lot of chainblocks happen, Gazelle or Exceed block Bale, Bale blocks Buff, Exceed also blocks Wolf) but instead on the summon after. Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf's recursion triggers when a monster is summoned in it's zone and Salamangreat Gazelle triggers on its own summon, which can be summoned to the zone a link monster points to. That means that Sea Archiver can increase the odds of some of your most important effects to go through. But wait, there's more. Sea Archiver, like Salamangreat Spinny is a Level 3 that banished itself if it leaves the field after having used its effect to extend. With Miragestallio, this is no longer an issue. So not only do you get to chainblock your valuable effects with this card, it also servers as an extender the following turn, which is were Salamangreat was already difficult to stop.   The presence of Miragestallio also made Bufferlo a much more attractive target for Cynet Mining. Miragestallio is essentially a Gazelle in the ED. Of course, you could also add Gazelle off of Cynet Mining and try to go into a r4nk play, but if you can't do that, you can always draw 2 and summon Gazelle afterwards. Or just take the +2 over the r4nk anyways, depending on the deck you're facing and how addicted you are to Dopamine.   Since last time I've dropped Parallel eXceed. It's just not as necessary anymore with Miragestallio around and this version is more backrow oriented. It's essentially "Overextending, the Card". I've since also added Ghost Belle back to the deck. It's a good handtraps and still nice to see past turn 1 since moving cards from the GY is a mechanic that's not only used to build boards but also by established boards. I played around with cutting Belle and instead playing Will at 2 and the Solenms at 3 each but I like the look of this deck as is. Solemn at 2 might seem a little weird but 4 is more than 3 and I don't really care which if these Solemns I see. I play a lot of backrow, so Judgment isn't just a worse Strike in this deck, they both have their strong suits and I'm usually happy with either, so I'm playing 4 instead of 3, that simple. I also changed the Heatleo to Knightmare Phoenix. People are siding Contact "C" against Tri-Brigade and you can't really out it without Phoenix. Lost me a YCS game and I'll be honest, that stung a little. I think I won't say goodbye to that card for a while now. Also finally fixed the Foxy, Spinny ratios. I still think 3 Foxy is fine in Bufferlo decks, since it's another target for Bufferlo but if you only play 5 copies out of the 2 cards, yeah, I'll admit you should play 3 Spinny - 2 Foxy.   These were my thoughts behind the changes I've made, I don't think there's much else to say and I think after my fourth Salamangreat list it's okay to not write half a book for once, so I'm outta here. See you on the next one. Oh, anyone else keeps forgetting the word Buffalo? I was thinking earlier how the real animal's spelled and it took me a solid minute to not think of 'Bufferlo' for once.

deck_excerpt: Fast paced casual deck with plenty of options and bounce back ability to keep the duel under your control.
deck_description: Elemental HERO's Blazeman and Shadow Mist take center stage with their ability to get Masked Hero Dark Law to the field quickly and disrupt opponents' plays and set up the graveyard for future plays. With just Elemental Hero Blazeman and Mask Change in the hand, Blazeman and use it's 2nd effect to send Shadow Mist from the deck to the grave simultaneously activating Shadow Mist's Graveyard effect to search any HERO from the deck and allowing Blazeman to be sent to the grave with Mask Change to summon Dark Law. Alternatively Elemental HERO Solid Soldier or Elemental HERO Liquid Soldier can quickly summon Shadow Mist from the hand or grave respectively fulfilling Shadow Mist's special summon requirement to search a Mask Change from the Deck.  The support throughout the deck focuses heavily on quickly getting to the right strategy for the duel with many cards that can quickly search the deck including Masked Hero Dian in the Extra deck who can destroy an opponent's monster to special summon Shadow Mist directly from the deck.  Traditional fusions also feature in the deck providing excellent support with Elemental HERO Sunrise at the forefront immediately bringing Miracle Fusion straight from the deck to the hand while offering a solid second effect and a nice attack point boost to your HEROs. Miracle Fusion can be utilized with the right pieces in the grave to immediately fusion summon Elemental HERO Absolute Zero which if paired with Form Change to summon Masked HERO Acid can wipe the opponent's field or Elemental HERO Gaia which additional to its useful effect can pair with Form Change to Summon Dark Law. Fusion Substitute features as my polymerization of choice being able to be searched by Blazemans 1st effect and allowing the deck to recycle fusion monsters in the grave and provide a free draw.  Plenty more options are possible throughout the deck to adapt as needed to your opponent's plays. The side deck provides alternative options including the powerful Super Polymerization which when paired with the correct Element Fusion HERO monster, (All feature either in the Extra or Side Deck) can remove almost anything from the opponent’s field including those with powerful protection effects. This can easily be implemented into the main deck as a permanent feature.

Second Turn OTK  Combo is Cyber Dragon Core + Spell card (except Power Bond) + Any Cyber Dragon Monser on hand, field or Gy. 1.-Bring Cyber Dragon Core with Cyber Emergency,  Cybernetic Horizon or Cyber Repair Plant (if possible) 2.- Summon Cyber Dragon Core, add Cyberdark World to your hand. 3.- Activate Cyberdark World, add Cyberdark Chimera, then normal summon it again with Cyberdark World Effect. 4.- Activate Cyber dark Chimera Effect, discard a Spell card, to add Power Bond 5.- When this Cyberdark Chimera Effect is activated, you can fusion using monster from your hand, field and Gy. 6.- Use Power Bond to Fussion Summon Chimeratech Dragon with 4200 atk, then use Chimeratech Dragon effect to clean spell/trap cards on your opponent side of the field, then activate second Chimeratech Dragon again, sending 2 light machine mosnters from the the to the graveyard, (Cyber Dragon Herz is a good option if you haven´t used its effect yet), to make up to 3 attacks. 7.- Optional if you got Cyber Dragon Seiger on the field, use its effect on Chimeratech for a 6300 Atk

Been playing this deck at locals after quarantine and it has done wonders for me. I have been playing HEROs since Stratos came back to 1 in September 2018, three years ago ever since as my main deck. When Stratos was unlimited I played him at three and played 3 e-call. Over time I have realized that he just really does nothing. This came up to me after my friend and I have been playing each other for so long. He used to negate Stratos and I would just combo off afterwards with Faris or fusion destiny that was in my hand. He stopped negating Stratos and waited until I would use faris and negate him. I was then dead in the water unless I drew my 3 of Fusion destiny. If I go Faris first and he negates, what am I going to do with normal summon Stratos? The only real thing I could do is search honest neos and attack if going second. I could search the evil hero if I had one but they too much for 1 card and will probably be reprinted soon. All I am trying to say is that Stratos is not the best normal summon in the deck. I have discovered that Vyon is my favorite thing to normal summon and that I don't even like doing the Faris combo anymore.  Normal summon Vyon send Shadow Mist is essentially the same thing as Normal summon Stratos, they both search any HERO monster. But the kicker is that Vyon has a second effect that you can use immediately after by banishing the shadow mist and searching a polymerization. Which is +1 in card advantage making Vyon so much better. The other notable differences between the two is that Vyon is dark so he can be used to make Dark Law, especially when the opponent uses Effect Veiler or Infinite Impermanence on your Vyon when he uses his effect. Sure you can mask change Stratos too to dodge the negation but you have to make Masked Hero Blast which takes up a whole extra deck slot and just isn't as impactful as Dark Law. Stratos is still a good card and I believe that two in the deck is a good number to run. I love searching a Stratos during combo for a followup in the next turn to blow up my opponents back row, its just so satisfying. He is also a great target for A Hero Lives and it hurts when you have only 1 Stratos and it is in your hand when you want to resolve A Hero Lives using him so I like two. He is also an Elemental Hero which is important when making any of the omni heros with super poly. That is why I prefer 2 Stratos 3 Vyon. As for the other potential normal summons, Liquid and Solid soldiers, I feel like Solid Soldier is just a win more card that is really clunky and I always find myself siding him out every game. Liquid soldier is my favorite card in the deck. I really can't play the deck without him anymore. Liquid being a draw 2 discard 1 twice in one duel gives me so much flexibility. I rarely use his normal summon effect unless I either have to or I am searching mask change with shadow mist turn one which does come up sometimes, especially with the one card combo of Fusion Destiny. So I run zero solid soldier and one liquid soldier.  For the rest of the Vision HEROs, even though I said I don't like the Faris combo anymore, I still opt to run 3 since it is an excellent bait card for handtraps/negates. If they let the effect to place a vision hero resolve then I can sit on the increase and then normal summon vyon and combo off from there. If they target my vyon I can tribute it with increase to dodge the effect and summon another one from my deck. Sure it can't use its first effect again but it can search poly too. The cool thing is if you run two polys you can search them both since Vyon's second effect is a soft once per turn. I don't find myself searching Faris and sometimes don't even use it's second effect if I want to summon anaconda or use super poly later in the turn. Often I am not even able to use Faris' second effect since I draw increase ALL THE TIME!!!! I will never bring increase back to two even if it is a garnet I don't care. I hate seeing the card. It's not like you lose just because you draw it since you can still discard it or use it as fusion material and get it in the grave for the grind. That's why I run 3 faris and 1 increase.  As for the Destiny HEROs, I used to run plasma ALL the time and loved the card. It was my favorite card. As I played when quarantine was over, I found myself never summoning the card and it just being a brick in my hand all the time. I summoned him one time and just got nibirued. It is just such a fragile card that takes too much to make so I cut it. I do miss the card but when Burst of Destiny comes out I will make a deck with it. The rest of the Destiny HEROs in the deck are pretty standard. 2 Malicious 1 Dynatag and 1 level 4. I usually play drawhand but I never really used his draw effect since I never wanted to give my opponent a card so I switched him out for Decider. It's effects can be super helpful in select match ups whereas drawhand is really only good with droll, which I don't have. I have never really used Celestial so he could be a good choice too. The cards are really bricky but Fusion Destiny is too good to pass up.  I run 8 hand traps. 3 Ash 2 Belle and 3 Impermanence. Just my preference since they are 3 very versatile cards that work in many scenarios at locals. 8 is a great amount to open at least 1 which is what I want in this deck. One of my favorite cards in the deck, Super Poly, I run at three. It has been an amazing card for me that has won most of my games. Whether I am fusing both of my opponents monsters in my draw phase going second, Using one of my monsters (preferably liquid soldier to draw two discard 1) and an opponents when they only have 1 big monster/ just don't meet starving venom or mudragon criteria, or using both of my monsters during the battle phase to OTK my opponent. Such a good card, especially since I can just set it going first. You can't do that with cards like lightning storm, Kaijus, or Dark Ruler. I either main deck cosmic cyclone or rivalry, I am still not sure which one. Maybe I should do half and half. My side deck is really rudimentary and mainly just for my locals.  When I win the die roll I usually choose to go first even though my end board is usually just Sunrise Vyon pass. In the past I usually overextended and lost to nibiru all the time. Nowadays I almost never go over 4 summons unless I know my opponent doesn't have Nibiru or I just don't care and can play through it. You can easily OTK using only 4 summons during the main phase in this deck.  The main combo I use is normal summon Vyon send Shadow Mist search Liquid soldier then banish Solid soldier search Poly. If I have a HERO monsters in my hand that I don't need I will use it and Liquid to make sunrise, otherwise I would use the Vyon and Liquid. Chain link 1 Liquid Chain link 2 Sunrise add Miracle Fusion draw 2 discard 1. usually I set some cards and end my turn there if going first. If I need Mask Change and have Fusion Destiny in my hand I will do the combo of making Dangerous with Shadow mist and Malicious then banish mali to summon mali link into cross bring back mali search liquid normal liquid special shadow search mask change set mask change pass turn.  Anyways how I play the deck is basically just using Liquid Soldier as a draw engine to draw handtraps and powerful cards like Super poly to interrupt my opponent and OTK them. I hope you like my decklist and sorry if this explination is rough, I am doing it in one take and not polishing it much. I just wanted to write out whats on my mind and I want to look back at this list in the future when new cards come out and this list will be a memory of past formats. Thanks.
have fun

deck_excerpt: Anti-special summoning control birbs that everyone will hate playing against.
deck_description:
FlunderEZPZ

The main play behind Flundereeze is starting a train of Normal Summons every turn while maintaining an oppressive board, especially on your opponent's turn. I imagine this archetype as Ursarctics if they were done right. :,) Note that the Normal Summon train consists of resolving every HOPT effect of your Flundereeze monsters while also recycling themselves from being banished. It won't be interrupted by removal, but negates will shut them down. Be careful that you can't stop the train to set up a Spell or Trap and then pick up where you left off without another way to Normal Summon again. PROS:
  • 1-card bread & butter combo.
  • Sets up an oppressive board with minimal effort.
  • Recycling power that environmentalists can envy.
  • Can recovers easily after board wipes.
  • Can ignore Special Summon floodgates.
  • Doesn't care about being banished, prefers it, in fact.
  • Every turn can be your turn.
CONS:
  • Overly linear strategy.
  • Easily stopped with negates and hand traps.
  • Approaches toxic territory.
   

Starters

  • Flundereeze x Robina (one card starter)
    • This is the most important birb you will have ever set your eyes on. Do whatever you can to maximize access to Robina.
    • The most common plan would simply be Robina -> Eaglen -> Empen -> Set backrow.
  • Flundereeze and the Mysterious Map / Terraforming / Gold Sarcophagus + any level 1 Flundereeze
    • Banish a Robina and it will come back to your hand immediately after you Normal Summon your drawn Flundereeze through this effect.
    • Mysterious Map lets you Normal Summon ON YOUR OPPONENT'S TURN if they Normal Summon.

Bosses

  • Flundereeze x Empen
    • Your primary choice to end with on your first turn.
    • Searches for any Flundereeze Spell or Trap to enable your disruptive play.
    • Blocks off effect activations of your opponent's Special Summoned monsters in Attack Position. Very anti-Link.
    • Can beat over most monsters with its halving effect.
  • Raiza the Mega Monarch
    • The meat of your disruptive strategy.
    • Tribute Summon this on your opponent's turn due to Mysterious Map or City of Dreams and spin back their setup.
    • Play this carefully enough and you can potentially lock their hand by spinning a brick back to the top of their deck and this card itself for continuous access.
  • Flundereeze x Snowl
    • Mainly for finishing off the game by enabling piercing damage for ALL of your monsters.
    • If your opponent depends on having their monsters face-up, its mass flip-down effect can come very handy.
  • Mist Valley Apex Avian
    • This is an omni-negate that bounces itself back as cost.
    • This isn't once per turn, so you can put it right back out of you have the resources.

Recycling

  • Flundereeze x Strich
    • Is like having access to DD Crow every turn.
    • Banish would be your own Flundereeze Spell/Traps if you want to recycle them.
    • Be careful that you must have a GY target to keep the Normal Summon train going.
  • Flundereeze x Toccan
    • Returns ANY banished Flundereeze card back to your hand, including your Spell/Traps.
    • Be careful to not return a banished Flundereeze with its own effect instead of Toccan's to keep the Normal Summon train going.

Flundereeze Backrow

  • Flundereeze and the City of Dreams
    • Activate this anytime for a free (level 4 or lower Winged Beast) Normal Summon.
    • In the GY, this banishes itself to become a Book of Eclipse when you Tribute Summon a level 7+ monster.
  • Flundereeze and the Scary Sea
    • If your opponent tries some funny business with an INHERENT Special Summon, you can negate that summon, bounce it back, and shut down Special Summons for the rest of their turn.
    • They get 3 Normal Summons in return, though, which not many decks can work well with anyways.
  • Flundereeze and the Unknown Wind
    • Whenever you do a big Tribute Summon, you can use ANY 1 of your opponent's cards instead (even Spell/Traps!)
    • Kind of like a Kaiju, but not quite because it's a send to GY effect.
    • Also a bonus mulligan.

Tech Cards

  • Pot of Extravagance
    • FREE 2 cards for a chance to get your starter.
  • Pot of Duality
    • FREE excavate because you don't care about about Special Summoning at all.
  • Book of Moon
    • This allows you to dodge targeting negates like Effect Veiler and Infinite Impermanence.
  • Called By The Grave
    • You lose hard to Droll & Lock Birb and Ash Blossom.
  • Harpie's Feather Duster
    • Anti-backrow. You don't want your starters to get Solemn'd or floodgated.
    • Synergizes well with Feather Storm below.
  • Harpie's Feather Storm
    • Negates activations for the whole turn if you have a WIND birb out.
    • If your opponent is FOOLISH enough to use backrow destruction this can search/recycle a Feather Duster for you.
  • Dimension Shifter
    • Banish everything. Do you care? No.
    • Can shut down many turn 1 plays.
    • Raiza can recycle this. 

Extra Deck

  • It's mainly used as fuel for Pot of Extravagance. 
  • If you really must, have Elder Entity N'tss in it.
  • Can be filled with bulk, expired drivers licenses, or Uno cards for all you care.

Side Deck

  • Crossout Designator + hand traps
    • Wanna really be unfair?
    • Target Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, Droll & Lock Birb, or Artifact Lancea to seal off major counterplays.
  • Dark Ruler No More
    • You need all the help you can get playing turn 2, especially if you're against something with at least 1 monster negate.
  • Twin Twister
    • Additional anti-backrow support.
    • Combo with Dimension Shifter to make the cost almost free.
  • Barrier Statue of Storm Winds
    • You can end your Normal Summon train with this.
    • Play this card if you don't like having friends.

deck_excerpt: New Nordic support synergises really well with Tri-Brigade's current state of affairs
deck_description:
Gameplay footage below ( https://youtube.com/watch?v=Yt8zQj3G3iM&feature=youtu.be )
Our prayers had been finally answered. As for the first time ever, we get real support for the gods themselves. However one thing is to be clear: the boar named "Gullinbursti" is possessed by Freyr (the god of fertility), and made by the sons of Ivaldi. To it's dismay, the golden boar is very effective at what it is suppose to do (special summon from Hand, and recover a Nordic monster from the GY). Not to mention that since it is a beast monster, it fits well in the Tri-Brigade package that offers expandable ways to get to Thor or swarm your board. The reason that there isn't a whole lot to say about Ivaldi though, is because he himself just searches a Nordic relic on Summon (or special summon if you control a Nordic monster). The Tri-Brigade package fits well with Thor's branch of the Nordic/Aesir archetype as not only they are capable of synergy with the Nordic Beast; but also speak for themselves as they did what they always do best. To my surprise, the real MVP of the Tri-Brigade archetype this time around was "Rugal the Silver Sheller". What he does basically is Special summon a (beast/beast-warrior/winged beast) monster from your GY during your opponents turn. This is very effective as to say that you have the new Nordic Relic (Svalinn) on the field, and Thor in your GY; this gives you the opportunity to tribute one of your Nordic beast to your GY to special summon Thor from your GY. As for the rest of the deck, "Tri-Brigade Revolt" still holds title as the most situationally important piece of the deck. However this time, I included a Sky-Striker toolkit due to the importance of a card called "Sky-Striker Mecha - Eagle Booster" (a card which basically protects your monsters from everything that isn't a Kaiju for a turn). Also included is Triple Tacitcs Talent as hand traps are still the forefront cornerstone to modern Yu-Gi-Oh antics (plus Draw power and hand information is bretty important). For the Extra deck, there isn't whole much to say about it as nothing really changed outside of adding in Thor and Gullveig to the Extra Deck for the Nordic engine to take its course.

His "Obelisk the Tormentor" is supported with "Soul Exchange", and if that fails, he implements parts of a Machine deck representing Kaiba's expertise in technology; he mainly uses his "XYZ" monsters offensively until he is able to Summon "Obelisk".
