deck_excerpt: Click on this if spell speed 2 nukes sound cool
deck_description: (Alright third time's a charm) Megaliths are one of my favorite archetypes in this game because the concept of a ritual archetype with only ritual monsters is the kind of innovation that makes this game fun. They are also extremely cheap, you can pick up a full megalith core for under 20$ and you can easily get this deck down to 150$ or less by cutting the expensive extra deck monsters like Zeus and Accesscode. They are nice to have, but not mandatory by any means. Also you can nuke your opponent on their turn which is just sick. Card Breakdown 3 Megalith Phul - This is the single best card in the entire archetype. It does literally everything you can want a card to do within reason. It recurs a ritual monster on summon to lessen the impact of the card deficits that are inherent in ritual summoning while also modulating its level for XYZ plays. Its second effect is even better, allowing you to ritual summon a monster from the deck at spell speed 2. This is insane. You get to special summon a monster from the deck, which is one of the strongest things you can do in this game because it is both searching and field presence, and it being spell speed 2 allows you to bring out Megalith Bethor on your opponent's turn to pseudo-nuke them in the middle of their combo. This guy is both your starter and your ender in most of the 2-3 card megalith combos and it carries the entire archetype on its back. 3 Megalith Ophiel - Ophiel mostly facilitates consistency by searching a Megaltih (usually Phul, but sometimes hagith) and then using itself as the material to summon them. Its also useful in a few combos where you could already search a megalith but using Ophiel as a middleman will make the end result better, usually by giving you an extra Bethor pop or Letting you use Phul's on summon effect to make it level 4. 3 Megalith Hagith - Hagith is the megalith backrow searcher, and while there isnt much of it, its still good enough to be worth searching. You can run 2 Hagith but from my experience you are pretty happy to see this in your opener so its worth the third copy. 2 Megalith Bethor - Bethor is the biggest playmaker Megaliths have. It essentially field nukes your opponent on summon which is always a welcome effect in any deck. It can brick your hands though because it relies on the other megaliths to set it up, so running 3 is not advised. 2 Megalith Aratron - Aratron used to be one of the best cards in the deck because of the hand trap ritual summon but since the block dragon ban finding the resources to use it effectively has become significantly harder. Its still worth playing because it offers solid protection and recycling for your other Megaliths and the spell speed 2 ritual summon can save you in a pinch, but its not the staple it used to be. 3 Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands -  Megaliths don't have a normal summon in their archetype so playing ritual monster stratos is a great boost to consistency and being level 4 makes it useful for XYZ plays with Phul. 3 Senju of the Thousand Hands - Megaliths don't have any ritual spells so Senju is effectively identical to Manju and its worth playing for the same reasons. 8 hand traps - I'm going to break my own unofficial rules here and just say you can run any 8 hand traps by preference. Outside of Nibiru which is risky to run maindeck none of the hand traps have that much synergy with Megaliths so just play whatever. 3 Megalith Unformed - The first effect of Unformed is barely ever relevant but that doesn't matter because the second effect boosts consistency and allows you to start your plays without a level 8 Megalith. Its also an important part of the decks best combos. 3 Dark Ruler No More - It breaks boards going second like nothing else and this deck can't really afford to discard for things like Forbidden Droplet or Super Polymerization. Run this or get steamrolled by Drytron :/ 3 Pot of Desires - You only have 2 one-of engine pieces so 3 desires is a no-brainer. 2 Cosmic Cyclone - Cyclone is mostly here to out annoying floodgates like There Can Be Only One and -ugh- Mystic Mine. 1 Treacherous Trap hole - This is for Rafflesia, as a pro tip don't XYZ summon Rafflesia until after you activate Pot of Desires and confirm that this isn't banished. 1 Megalith Emergence - This is what you usually search off Hagith because you can use Emergence to summon a Phul from grave which can use its effect to summon Bethor to nuke your opponent at spell speed 2. After that it gives you a solid grind game. Extra Deck 1 Abyss dweller - Its a good floodgate XYZ monster to end your combos on. 1 Castel the Skyblaster Musketeer - Its Castel, this deck can make a rank 4. This bird person was a knightmare before knightmares were a thing. 1 Traptrix Rafflesia - Another rank 4 option to end on, popping 2 cards by sending Treacherous Trap Hole is a very strong disruption but if you can already make a spell speed 2 Bethor it can be a little redundant. 1 Baguska, the Terribly Tired Tapir - The ultimate stalling tactic for rank 4 decks everywhere. If your opponent is winning, make baguska and try to topdeck DRNM. 1 Gallant Granite - Usually not as good as the other rank 4s but its nice to have around because the search can unclog you draws, with megaliths needing at least 2 card to do anything and all that. 1 Number 97: Draglubion - Megaliths can also make rank 8 somewhat easily which makes a Draglubion engine pretty good here as a negate and beatstick or as an otk. 1 Number 100: Numeron Dragon -  For Draglubion. 1 Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy -  For Draglubion. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder - Its zeus in a deck that can make XYZ monsters. It can be a bit redundant with Bethor, But again, its Zeus. 1 Knightmare Phoenix - Its a knightmare. 1 I:P Masquerena - I had some extra deck space free so i just threw this in because we are playing knightmares. You almost never make it but its there. 1 Black Luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos -  Its really funny to just slam this absolute beast down on someone who forgot to put a dragoon out in their deck and watch them lose. 1 Knightmare Unicorn -  Okay i should probably explain why extra deck monsters with removal effects are so good for the sake of clarity and newer players. Having an answer to your opponent's most threatening cards in the forever accessible extra deck completely removes the luck aspect from whether you can remove things, which is a pretty big deal because then you don't have to play cards like Raigeki so that you have access to removal. 1 Accesscode talker - Having accesscode in your extra deck means you can always generate a ton of damage to otk your opponent and that's why its 100+ dollars and played in basically everything. 1 Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess - Its the best link monster that has the word negate on it, and while again its usually better to just make an XYZ, having it doesn't hurt. Basic Combos Phul + Manju/Senju NS Manju/Senju Manju/Senju summon ef search a level 8 Level 8 hand ef tributing Manju/Senju to summon Phul Phul 1st ef add the level 8 back to hand Phul 2nd ef tributing itself to summon Ophiel from deck Ophiel ef search Hagith Ophiel ritual summon ef tributing itself to summon Hagith Hagith ef search Emergence Set Emergence On your opponent's turn, activate emergence summoning Phul from GY Phul ef tributing the level 8 in hand summons Bethor with 2 pops, or more if you tribute hagith and/or phul from the field even though you dont have to A level 8 and a level 4 megalith work in place of Manju/Senju Activate level 8, tributing level 4 to summon Phul Phul ef add the level 8 back to hand The combo is the same from there   Unformed + any megalith except Phul Unformed tributing the megalith to summon Phul if it is level 4 and Ophiel which searches Phul then tributes itself to summon Phul if its level 8 Phul 1st ef return a level 4 Megalith to hand Phul 2nd ef tributing the level 4 to summon Ophiel into Hagith if the original Megalith was level 4 or straight into Hagith if it was level 8 Hagith ef add Emergence Overlay Hagith and Phul to summon Abyss Dweller or Traptrix Rafflesia Set Emergence Opponents turn After you activate XYZ monster's ef detaching Phul Activate Emergence Summon Phul from GY if you have materials in hand to use Phul's effect summoning Bethor you can do so with 2-4 pops depending on the level of the original Megalith and how many materials you have in hand   Unformed + Manju/Senju NS Manju/Senju Manju/Senju ef search Ophiel Unformed tributing Ophiel to summon Phul Phul 1st ef add Ophiel back to hand Phul 2nd ef tributing Ophiel to summon Hagith Hagith ef add Emergence Overlay Hagith and Manju/Senju for Abyss Dweller or Traptrix Rafflesia Set Emergence On opponent's turn Activate Emergence summoning Ophiel Phul 2nd ef tributing itself and Ophiel to summon bethor with 2 pops, or 3 if your XYZ monster has already detatched Hagith to activate its effect

Why the Pheonix enforcer? ecclesia recursion from gy and well its just powerful too.  Why so many Iris? One of the few decks it can benefit from both the banishes and draws for example Grand Duke, only thing that desires can potentially put an outright end to if unlucky is killing fusion destiny by banishing its targets  The decks primary combos are straight forward  Dragon Sword + any Wyrm/Swordsoul // Dragon sword in hand add Tai A, summon Tai A banish Dragon sword summon token making either yang zing synchro Tai A send Mo Ye, yang zing sacrifice summon Mo Ye reveal swordsoul or wyrm summon token, synchro grand sword master (atm dont get Mo Ye +1) add tactician send sword soul for tactician for ss summon token make any L10 synchro you wish (based on hand may wish to use search for trap/spell or even banish)  Mo Ye + any Wyrm/ Swordsoul summon Mo Ye reveal swordsoul or wyrm summon token, synchro grand sword master cl1 Sword Master cl2 Mo Ye get +1 first just incase you draw a duplicate add tactician send sword soul for tactician for ss summon token make any L10 synchro you wish  As for those like me who aim to make the deck when the cards are availible yes the tech choices are expensive but very very very easily substituted dont need verte only for consistency on pheonix and most hand traps and coounter traps can be swapped for basic floodgates other tech choices and engines a great thing about swordsoul you can play literally any tech choices because its own engine is so consistent and not particularly reliant on anything but desires may be important for boosting consistency through its ratios.

deck_excerpt: Once a deck for blind 2nd OTKs turned into a decent deck. Not possible, right?
deck_description: ZW's are for Leo Utopia ray, detach, equip one from deck. With the addition of Pegasus Twin saber, 2 level 4s turn into 2 monster negates. Tornado Bringer and Lightning Blade are just tech cards, if you have the possibility to search another ZW, always add Tornado. It's free targeting protection and, most importantly, 100 more atk than Lightning blade. With 2 of each of the Onomat trio, Utopic Onomatopoeia, Gagagacoat, and Gogogoglove, 3 Utopic Astral Hope, 3 Astral Kuriboh, and 2 ZS - Ascended sage, you have all you need for a great rank 4 engine. The onomat trio, when all 3 are on the field, are essentially 6 lvl 4s. The basic combo with these guys is:  Summon Utopic Onomatopoeia, use effect, Glove and Coat, xyz with Glove and Utopic for utopia double, double detach glove, go into Leo, Leo effect, detach Utopic, equip Twin Saber. Then you use Coats effect, to revive Utopic. And gloves effect to revive itself. Then you xyz (any materials) into ZS - Utopic Sage. You then use Sages effect, ss Ascended sage from the deck. Ascended sage with the left over lvl 4, and here's where you make a decision. 1 Decision goes into utopia, ending on a utopia dragner with 4 materials, or a utopic Draco Future. For the Dragner Route, you go into Utopia with Ascended and the left over lvl 4. Use Ascended (Technically Utopia, since Ascended gives it an extra effect) to search Hyper Rank Up Magic Hope Force, then (NOT USING HYPER) summon Utopia Prime, then use the Rank Up Magic to go into a Utopia Dragner. Then use Dragner, detatch any 2 materials, summon Hope Harbinger (Don't use Hyper Rank Up Magics Gy Effect.) Then, during the opponents end phase, you can use Dragner to summon Heart-eartH Dragon, using Hyper Rank Up's gy effect, to attack itself to it. Then you can use Heart-eartH to banish all of the opponents monsters. Only do this if you plan for an OTK Next turn. Now, for the Utopic Draco Future Route, use Ascended Sage and the leftover lvl 4 to go into Gagagaga Magician, then use Gagagaga Magician with the ZS - Utopic Sage to go into Utopic Future (Only those 2, the monsters on Gagagaga are detatched), then go into Utopic Draco Future. The Route with Dragner ends of 2 Monster negates, and 1 spell negate, and at the ep, banish all of your opponents monsters. With the Draco Future, 3 Monster negates, with the added benefit of taking control of the opponents monster when you negate it on the field with Draco Future.     And good morning, that was very tiring to read, wasn't it. Well there's more. great... Luckily it's only about 4 cards. The first is Zexal Entrust. This one is just when you need another target to search with Utopic Astral Hope. Basically a fallback. Feel free to remove it, but sometimes it's decent. The 2nd is Chain Summon. This is another one of, just like Entrust. It's for when you got enough cards to go into the Dragner Route, and when you still have enough space, you can use chain summon to summon Utopic Future, since there's no requirement for summoning and it's a rank 1. The 3rd card is Numbers Protect. This is also just another searcher for Utopic Astral hope, really powerful, Omni Negate, definitely a keep. The last card is Zexal Construct. This card is more used to unbrick your hand. In a lot of cases, you may draw cards you don't want to. Those 3 cards are the 2 Double or nothings, and Pegasus Twin saber. Construct sends a card from your hand to the deck, then adds one of a few Utopic Support cards. Most of the time you'll search a ZW, like Tornado Bringer. This combined with the normal combo lines and it being a searchable way to unbrick your hand (Utopic Astral Hope) is AMAZING. And for the Droll & Lock Bird, you can replace that for your hand-trap of choice.
Drytron

Competitive Pure Evil Twin Deck  

Card by Card Explanation:

Starters The two main starters of the deck are Live☆Twin Lil-la and Live☆Twin Ki-sikil. It is preferable to start with Lil-la if possible, as it gives you access to Live☆Twin Ki-sikil Frost, a card with a useful GY effect. You want to prioritise opening with whichever Twin whose matching extender you have access to, to ensure you're able to play through interruptions such as Ash, Veiler or Imperm. Live☆Twin Lil-la One of the two starters in the deck, if possible start with Lil-la as you'll gain access to Live☆Twin Ki-sikil Frost's GY effect. Live☆Twin Ki-sikil The deck's other starter, you'll start with this if you do not have access to Lil-la. Extenders The extenders are your tools for if your opponent tries to interrupt your plays. They allow you to continue your combo through your opponent's disruptions and are a large consistency boost in achieving your end board. Live☆Twin Lil-la Treat The matching Twin for Ki-sikil, she's the weaker of the two Twin extenders, due to her underwhelming GY effect, her main purpose is to act as an extender. Live☆Twin Ki-sikil Frost The matching Twin for Lil-la, her GY effect is very useful, banishing herself from the GY to draw a card if your opponent adds a card from their Main Deck to their hand. Live☆Twin Home Very versatile card, it can be used as a starter, or as an extender that can summon either twin from deck. This card will lock you to Live☆Twin monsters which will lock you from certain extra deck plays. Utility These are the other archetypal cards that boost consistency and have other benefits. Live☆Twin Sunny's Snitch The archetypal ROTA, it searches any Live☆Twin monster. Secret Password Secret Passcode is a very flexible searcher that can add any archetypal Spell/Trap to hand. Evil★Twin Challenge This card functions similarly to Call of the Haunted. It lets you recover from losing Evil★Twin's Trouble Sunny during your opponent's turn by reviving Evil★Twin Ki-sikil. Extra Deck Evil★Twin Ki-sikil One of 2 link 2s the archetype has at its disposal. Ki-sikil's quick-effect allows her to revive a Lil-la monster from the GY, this allows her to revive Evil★Twin Lil-la in order to pop a card on field. Evil★Twin Lil-la The other part of the Evil★Twin pair. Lil-la's quick-effect allows her to revive a Ki-sikil monster from the GY, this allows her to revive Evil★Twin Ki-sikil in order to draw one card. Evil★Twin's Trouble Sunny The boss monster of the deck. Sunny has the quick-effect to tribute itself to revive a Lil-la and Ki-sikil monster from the GY, this allows you to activate the trigger effects of both link 2s to pop a card on field and to draw one card. This effect can be used during the battle phase which nets you a potential 5500 points of damage, you can then re-link both link 2s into a Sunny in Main Phase 2 to maintain disruption on your opponent's turn. Sunny's GY effect sends one Evil★Twin monster from your deck, field or hand to the GY to remove a card from the field. It's important to note that this effect does not target or destroy therefore it can bypass pseudo-towers cards like Dragoon. The send target for this effect is the main deck Evil★Twins Ki-sikil Lil-la. Unchained Abomination Abom is a powerhouse card in the deck, its ability to pop extra cards as well as pop a card in the End Phase allows you to pop a potential 3+ cards per turn when used in conjunction with the effect of Evil★Twin Lil-la.

deck_description: gonna beat jacobs ass

Que tal amigos, aqui tenemos un deck cortesia de Mario Piña. Lo que tenemos aquí, es un mazo con el que estrategias tipo combo, que necesitan dejar dejar un campo bien establecido o generar/reciclar recursos para poder avanzar en el duelo ven truncados sus esfuerzos. Esto es gracias a que el mazo ya sea siendo turno 1 o 2 tiene bastantes posibilidades de darnos algunos problemas durante nuestros turnos (si no tenemos cartas muy especificas dentro de nuestra estrategia para evitarlo), ya que la cantidad de interrupciones, floodgates y recursos que puede generar son bastante potentes. Cartas como Dimension Shifter y Macro Cosmos, provocan que cualquier estrategia que necesite recursos en cementerio (Drytron, Tri-Brigade, PK, entre otros), no logren hacerse con ellos para continuar sus jugadas o reciclar recursos. Así mismo el control que le generan cartas como Thunder King Rai-Oh, Inspector Boarder, Fossil Dyna Pachycephalo, There Can Only Be One y Summon Limit, son bastante útiles, pues todas ellas afectan directamente al oponente. Del lado de las trampas que ayudan a controlar un poco mas el juego de nuestro oponente tenemos Crackdown, para robarle un monstruo (starter o extender y de ser posible monstruo jefe) a nuestro oponente e interrumpir sus jugadas; también tiene a su disposición  Solemn Judgment y Solemn Warning que junto con Thunder King Rai-Oh evitaran cualquier Special Summon de nuestro oponente, aún si no tenemos a Fossil Dyna Pachycephalo en el campo; siendo de todas ellas Solemn Warning la que representa un mayor problema, ya que esta niega invocación Normal, Flip (lo que es bastante útil ya que hay monstruos que requieren hacer flip una vez colocados para activar sus efectos) y por ultimo pero no menos importante niega Special Summon tanto inherente (Cyber Dragon, Kaijus, Pankratops, etc.), como asistida (Monster Reborn, Tri-Brigade Revolt, Red-Eyes Fusion, Nibiru, etc.). Para la generación de recursos en caso de no tener una mano tan favorable tenemos las ollas indicadas para esta estrategia que son Pot of Desires, Pot of Extravagance y Pot of Duality, siendo Desires y Extravagance quienes potenciaran al monstruo jefe de esta estrategia Gren Maju Da Eiza, el cual recordemos que se suma 400 ATK/DEF por cada carta baneada (nuestra), y Duality la cual nos puede dar el robo que necesitamos sin arriesgar mucho pues no requerimos tanto la Special Summon. Ahora bien el Extra Deck tiene 2 funciones, siendo de las principales pagar costo de Extravagance e Eater of Millions los cuales requieren banear boca abajo, exclusivamente del Extra Deck. La segunda función viene de la mano de Gizmek Orochi, que aunque no nos podemos hace de él mas que robandolo; si se tiene el suficiente control en el juego, a la larga podremos hacernos con hasta 2 de ellos en el campo e ir por los XYZ que necesitemos según la situación, si necesitamos quitar algún monstruo molesto que no pueda ser destruido por efectos o sea intargeteable, tenemos a Dingirsu o si queremos ir por el OTK tenemos el combo Draglubion, el cual solo se puede detenido si el oponente tiene algo que niegue efectos sin hacer target. Para finalizar en el Side Deck vemos una carta bastante interesante Super Polymerization, pues con ella podemos deshacernos de algunos monstruos del oponente que representen algo con lo que no podemos lidiar tan fácilmente, esto lo logramos gracias a que por lo regular nuestros oponentes siempre trataran de ir por el duelo y dejar al menos 3 monstruos; y si es el caso que robamos o tenemos en mano Instant Fusion, esto nos facilita un poco lograrlo pues podemos invocar Thousand-Eyes Restrict y con ello conseguir el monstruo que nos pudiera faltar; pero si nuestro oponente no esta listo , podemos equiparnos un monstruo suyo con Thousand-Eyes, despues podemos traer Relinquished Anima con Thousand-Eyes asi ya le enviamos un monstruo al GY a nuestro oponente y con Relinquished Anima le robaremos un segundo monstruo, para así cerrar con Super Polymerization y quitarnos el resto que pudiera tener en campo. Para conocerlo mejor, solo descargarlo y pruebalo en tu app/programa para jugar YGO! en linea. Nos vemos y..., Buen Duelo.

deck_excerpt: A cheap ($100-ish) Dragon Link deck which is actually fun both to play and be played against! Note that this deck is not very viable in tournaments an
deck_description: My first ever decklist! Someone on Dueling Nexus asked me for this decklist, so I've decided to make one on YGOProDeck. This deck can reliably get out an Borrelend Dragon + a dark level 8 Synchro of your choice while remaining cheap (~$87 on TCGPlayer with a $20 Borrelend for a total of $108). Note that this deck is made as an fun deck for local plays, although you can "competitively" play this against top decks by adding staples, expensive cards and a proper side deck. Card choices, basic combos & Alternatives -3x Black Metal Dragon: Your best starter. Normal summon, then link it into Striker Dragon to add BSL & Darkness Metal. Banish Striker Dragon for Darkness, reborn Black Metal then link into Romulus. Add Dragon Ravine ( or Divine Lance for a free dragon if you already have Tracer in your starting hand) and Wyvern as discard fodder (sometimes synchro material with Romulus' effect). Special summon Tracer (and possibly another Rokket) using your BSL and work toward an Borrelend Dragon + Tracer using Elpy, Quadborrel and Dillingerous Dragon. If you've used Tracer's effect before, use Borrelend to reborn your level 4 Rokket is always an option, but I usually save it for something like an Shelrokket or Silverrokket. x1 Magnarokket/Shelrokket/Silverrokket/Anesthrokket Dragon: Fun cards, although gimmicky to resolve. Magna provides non-targeting removal, Shel literally "shoots" your opponent's monster with an interesting "fragmentation" effect, Silver can sometimes win you the game (by banishing your opponent's single copy of Meow-Meow-Mu, etc) and Anes as a free negate. They all float into other Rokkets during the End Phase, providing you the ability to push for game using Borrelsword or powerful level 8 Synchros such as Draco Berserker of the Tenyi. Always replaceable with hand traps if you already have them. x2 Rokket Caliber: Nice extender that gets your Rokkets in position, also is a free level 4 tuner. This card haven't been released in the TCG though. If released, I think that it won't really change the $108 price of our deck as a common in BODE. (Seriously, I pulled a playset without spending more than ~$5 on 3 packs.) Ditch it for other cards if other players insult you for playing an OCG card. x3 Forbidden Chalice: Budget replacement of Dark Ruler No More and Forbidden Droplet. Swap them out if you already have one of those expensive cards. x1 Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend: You won't be using this card regularly, but sometimes this can be more than enough to ruin your opponent's day. Board wipe + Burn, also has nice interactions with Borreload Dragon. 1x Beelze: Fun to beat your opponent. 1x Draco Berserker of the Tenyi: Your worse but cheaper Borrelsword. 1x Firewall eXceed: Can become a cheap 5k beatstick. -If you have the financial ability, go for 3x Crossout Designator+ 1 each of Nibiru and Ash Blossom. This deck dies to Nibiru and Ash and a single copy of Called By The Grave isn't going to help. (If you're broke like us Vietnamese duelists, use proxies to play with your friend. A $100 card is about 1/4 the average monthly salary of us.) Thanks for reading this! Hope you enjoy dueling with my decklist! Post-Script: Sorry for my broken English ;-; I'm not very good at writing long guides. UPDATE: Ditched the Chaos Ruler for an Borreload Savage. UPDATE#2: Knightmare Unicorn & Chaos Ruler to replace Firewall eXceed and Beelze. Thanks for the great advice!

deck_description: nothing much

Adamancipator is a weird deck. It easily synchro climbs into big boss monsters, but there is no nice guaranteed combo. Instead you're forced to rely on a little luck and some good deck building to make your huge boards. However, with that little bit of luck the deck can consistently put Apollo + 2-3 Synchros on the board at the end of turn 1. If you like negating effects a lot this might be the deck for you. It is very good at stealing Game 1s, but doesn't side deck that well. Anyways, let's get into the deck list.  We're a Sekka's Light deck. I didn't really have room to run a lot of spells and traps when I was near the end of deck building, and while you have to side this out often it seems too good to run a better Pot of Greed not to run it.  3 of each Adamancipator Tuner is essential to your deck. When things are going well for you the deck will use all 3 of these in a turn, and really to goal is to use as many of your "monster maker" cards in a turn as possible. I can't imagine the deck will ever run fewer than all 9 of these, they are your main starters, your best extenders, and the whole reason the deck is a deck. Rock goodstuff doesn't seem like a deck without them that's for sure.  3 Doki Doki. This is a great hit off of an Adamancipator, a good starter in its own right, and one of the effects you really want to go off in your turn. It's also nice to have level 2 non-tuners for Synchro climbing, and this is the best level 2 Rock monster that isn't a tuner.  We're running the Prank Kids engine to Link climb. One copy of Rocksies results in a Dodo-Doodle-Doo and a Rocksies on the field while adding 2 cards to your hand, one of which is a level 4 EARTH Rock monster, very relevant for some combo plays. What you do with those resources is up to you, but this is another one of those effects you want to get in a turn, and an amazing hit off of Adamancipators, and sometimes a decent starter in its own right. Dropsies and Fansies gives you a little bit of a buffer, and also gives you more ways to turn on your Risen Adamancipators.  Plaguespreader Zombie is a brick for Needlefibre, getting to Link climb into Needlefibre while generating the resources to Synchro climb is really quite good. This card also allows you to stack the top of your deck for your Adamancipator triggers etc, very useful actually, particularly since this deck doesn't require a lot of resources from the hand to combo off, but rather some luck in your hits.  Penguin Soldier is a brick for Penguin Brave, not much to say. You almost never summon this, but you want it for when you need it.  3 Koa'ki Meiru Supplier are our main extender, it's a level 4 EARTH Rock monster that special summons itself, so it's a no-brainer. You can do cool things with the Guardian it searches, so try not to forget this second effect.  3 Koa'ki Meiru Guardian are also obligatory. Hand traps are good, but being able to hit this really puts a hamper on them. The deck makes negates early to stop Nibiru quite easily. It also fills its hand with Rock monsters, so this card can often represent an additional negate. Usually if I hit 7+ negates it is because of a copy or two of this card. Can be a decent normal summon sometimes too.  3 Tackle Crusader. We need level 4 EARTH Rock monsters for the deck. This one does something if you're going second, probably wouldn't be playable in usual circumstances but the deck necessitates a high density of Rock monsters which means we run this card.  1 Gate Blocker, run for the same reasons as above, the absence of playable rock extenders leaves me running any trash that could have upside. Does protect Apollo from Imperm among other things, so this card feels pretty good when it is good.  1 Weeping Idol. It is the wrong attribute, but it is mostly a generic rock extender, and it gives us a fourth level 2 which is actually pretty useful.  3 Madolche Petingcessoeur. It's a generic level 4 extender, run whichever one of those you think has the least downside. I think it is this one, though it does sort of limit you from playing hand traps, so the plan is to side these out when you need Ash.  3 Tenyi Spirit - Adhara. It's a generic tuner you can special summon. Your biggest turns require a little luck and starting with these and and the Madolche monster. It basically only makes Needlefibre, but you want to make Needlefibre, so it is good enough given the limited space Rock monsters occupy. Also not a rock, oh well.  3 Nib. It has fringe advantages over other hand traps in the deck, and is usually high impact in the matchups you need hand traps most. There isn't really space for hand traps in the deck, but we need as many playable Rock monsters as possible and this is, in fact, one of them.     In the Extra Deck, we have the Prank Kids engine to "turn on" Rocksies. Pretty self explanatory, generate a bunch of resources off of one hit. We have Apollo - you're almost always trying to end on this to pile the negates on, very important. We have the two playable Risen Adamancipators - Raptite is occasionally an extra interruption, and a half decent one, but is mostly just an engine card that gives you an extra Adamancipator effect in a turn. Unlike the tuners, it can hit the tuners, so it is pretty decent. Dragite helps break boards and also helps pile on spell negates, and is also important just for being an Adamancipator monster. You try and make this before Apollo to protect her from Imperm. Needlefibre summons Plaguespreader Zombie while link climbing which is important to your combo. Herald, Savage, and Crystal Wing are all your generic boss monsters you make to set up negates. Penguin Brave is interesting in the deck for a couple reasons. You need another Synchro 6 to make for Synchro climbing, if possible it should generate resource, and if possible it should serve as an interruption. Prenguin Brave happens to do all of that pretty well. Sometimes you have to mind your zones and not summon a Penguin with it, and you're mostly just trying to climb it into an 8, but it isn't bad as an interruption in a pinch. Gallant Granite searches you an Adamancipator monster, usually Researcher, helping turn 2 level 4s into Needlefibre + an Adamancipator effect, very relevant to trying to activate all 4 Adamancipator effects in a turn. Abyss Dweller is a good floodgate and worth running for GY matchups. Accesscode and Unicorn are to break boards going second as well as for follow-up plays. I:P is only okay in this deck, but helps put up an extra interruption when your materials don't Synchro together.     Side decking is weird for this deck. You need a mass of Rock monsters, you want your extenders, and Sekka's Light and the Madolche monster kind of narrow your plays down. You mostly don't really want to side, which makes the deck a lot worse in Bo3. Still, there are a few packages I wanted to run. 3 Anti-Magic Arrows and 1 Red Reboot are here for trap decks - you can absolutely break an average trap board after using anti-magic arrows, and as we don't run other spells and traps aside from the Sekka's Light it is easy enough to side Sekka's light out and just blow out the trap deck. Gamma is a good high-impact hand trap that is fairly generic and doesn't put monsters in the GY for the Madolche monster, so I think these are kind of a must-run. The rest is a crapshoot. I decided DRNM is a good emergency card to have against combo, then I slammed in Ash and Imperm for some more good generic cards you can add in to increase hand trap density if that plan makes the most sense.

deck_excerpt: Fun fishy deck thats pretty good.
deck_description: Main Deck: The Legendary Fisherman - Used to get out The Legendary Fisherman III (boss card). Can be normal summoned without tribute if A Legendary Ocean is on the field. Can also be summoned with Lantern Shark. The Legendary Fisherman II - Same as The Legendary Fisherman, but unaffected by monster card effects. The Legendary Fisherman III - Banishes opponent's monsters on special summon. Can't be destroyed by battle or card effects (also unaffected by Spells/Traps). Can be summoned if The Legendary Fisherman, or The Legendary Fisherman II is on the field. Citadel Whale - Wipes opponent's monster zone and can be summoned from GY. Warrior of Atlantis - Can be used to get A Legendary Ocean, or XYZ. Also decent attack. Buzzsaw Shark - One of 2 cards mainly used for XYZ. Summon, then activate to get Lantern Shark and XYZ to Valiant Shark Lancer (can detach one for a monster pop), then XYZ into Full Armored Crystalzero Lancer. Lantern Shark - The other main XYZ material. Can be used for previous combo, or can Normal Summon to get a lvl 5 monster Special Summoned. Ex: Normal Summon Lantern Shark, then Special Summon The Legendary Fisherman, then tribute that to Special Summon The Legendary Fisherman III. Abyss Soldier - Used to return opponent's cards back to hand. Beautunaful Princess - Used to get Buzzsaw Shark and start XYZing. Barrier Statue of the Torrent - Stops opponent from special summoning. A Legendary Ocean - Field Spell. Acts like Umi, but reduces all water monsters' lvl by 1, meaning you can Normal Summon The Legendary Fisherman and The Legendary Fisherman II without tributes. Rage of Kairyu-Shin - Pretty cool removal card. Moray of Greed - Pot of Greed water version. Feast of the Wild LV5 - Can Summon A Legendary Fisherman. Monster Reborn - Not sure what this does. Sea Stealth Attack - Can retrieve A Legendary Ocean from GY. Protects Spells/Traps & lets the Fisherman cards basically win any battle. White Howling - Spell negates. Paleozoic Dinomischus - Pops a card and returns as a normal monster (Water) if a trap is activated. Solemn Strike - Nice for denying plays. Tornado Wall - Protects against battle damage if A Legendary Ocean is up.   Extra Deck: Toadally Awesome - Omni-Negate summoned by Bahamut Shark. Bahamut Shark - Summon, then detach for Toadally Awesome. Abyss Dweller - Extra attack is always nice. Number 101: Silent Honor ARK - Eats an opponent's monster. Number 103: Ragnazero - Situational but works. Evigishki Merrowgeist - Also situational but works. Number 19: Freezadon - Can be used to help with the XYZ detaching. Number 11: Big Eye - Hard to get out but takes control of opponent's monsters. Mistar Boy - More ATK for the Water bois. Knightmare Phoenix - Can be used to destroy Spell/Trap. Valiant Shark Lancer - XYZ from Lantern Shark & Buzzsaw Shark (possible detach for a monster pop), then XYZ into Full Armored Crystalzero Lancer. Full Armored Crystalzero Lancer - XYZ from Valiant Shark Lancer then you can detach for a one turn negate on all monsters. Also has a lot of ATK.

"With the advent of the avaricious Agnimazud and his kin, alchemic riders of the blaze blast into the battle! The Metalfoes are armed with an arsenal of alchemically-enchanted vehicles. From aurum ATVs to argent areial machines. By merging with their rides, these alloyed warriors are able to combat the dangerous dreadwyrm and aid the Dracoslayer in his quest to eliminate the eminating evils. Burn up the Soul! Metalfoes Fusion!" The Metalfoes are an interesting deck, being more of a Fusion deck that happens to sue Pendulum monsters. I would say that this would make them somewhat self sufficient and thus resilient to banlist hits...if not for the fact that one of the banned cards was Electrumite. The general gist here is to use the monsters to create fusions and recur resources and then try to swing for game. Off-themed cards here include:
  • Link Spider: Decent extender given the normal monster focus
  • Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon, Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon and Performapal Odd-Eyes Dissolver: Which this isn't a pendulum deck per se (in terms of playstyle that is), it does still consist entirely of Pendulum monsters and is a Fusion deck so Vortex fits like a glove. Dissolver and Absolute offer ways to get to Vortex with the former properlly summoning it so that it can be revived if necessary and possible.
  • GranSolfachord Musecia: Closest thing we got to Electrumite and while she can't get you draws she can at least offer some way of fixing scales once you used their effects.
  • Dowsing Fusion: more of a meme tech, but since we do play Absolute and since fusing from the hand from the other spells doesn't put them in the ED it is more likely to be live here compared to other Pendulum decks.
  • Unexpected Dai, Painful Decision, Rescue Rabbit and Rescue Hamster: Normal Monster support and pendulum support, though some do need you to already have a copy on hand to work.
The side deck is purely conceptual. That said with the advent of certain cards, Engraver of the Mark might be a decent budget option. Other possible options include Greater Polymerisation if you want Crimsonite to not be a Vanilla (wont work with the other ones), Some Rank 4s with Goldriver and Hamster/Rabbit (Vimana is out until there is a Level 5 in theme pendulum monster, and even then that is imcomptable with Rabbit) and a Magician engine with Chronogrpah is you want to play it like the average pendulum combo deck.
